  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1039552090" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1039552090" />
    <a title="Blair" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/272909-blair"><img alt="Blair" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618512192p2/272909.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1039552090?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blair" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blair" href="/user/show/272909-blair">Blair</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/55921605-hotel-du-lac">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=read-on-kindle">read-on-kindle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=booker-prize">booker-prize</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=1980s-release">1980s-release</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1039552090" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2321154796711502486">Edith, a &apos;writer of romantic fiction under a more thrusting name&apos;, checks in to the Hotel du Lac, a traditional establishment in a quiet lakeside town in Switzerland. (Cover notwithstanding, I pictured it as a grey and dreary place.) She has fled some upset or scandal at home in London; it isn&apos;t specified at first, but it&apos;s bad enough for her to accept her friends&apos; apparent insistence that she &apos;disappear for a decent length of time&apos;. As so often in Brookner&apos;s fiction, Edith is a character it&apos;s a</span>
  <span id="freeText2321154796711502486" style="display:none">Edith, a 'writer of romantic fiction under a more thrusting name', checks in to the Hotel du Lac, a traditional establishment in a quiet lakeside town in Switzerland. (Cover notwithstanding, I pictured it as a grey and dreary place.) She has fled some upset or scandal at home in London; it isn't specified at first, but it's bad enough for her to accept her friends' apparent insistence that she 'disappear for a decent length of time'. As so often in Brookner's fiction, Edith is a character it's almost impossible to write about without using the word 'spinster'; she characterises herself as timid, helpless, and lost in a brutal world; and the story takes place in a faded milieu that seems much earlier than the 1980s.<br /><br />Brookner's typical protagonist fascinates me because she (in the books I've read so far, it's always been she) is hamstrung by entirely invented, entirely <em>unimportant</em> things: manners, social mores, extremely strict behavioural norms, the need to stick to a rigorous routine. It's difficult to read <em>Hotel du Lac</em> now and not want to scream when Edith returns to 'the question of what behaviour most becomes a woman', or thinks of her own life as something over which she is unable to exert control – indeed, the fact that she's allowed herself to be forced out of the country (!) in the first place is infuriating. At the same time, I can't help but see the Brookner novels I've read as antecedents of the current glut of novels about young(ish) women attempting to untangle existential crises. Edith's anxieties are reflected in many of these stories, even if they are filtered through more contemporary concerns (burnout and career problems instead of humiliation and social strictures; financial concerns instead of desperation for marriage; depression instead of some inviolable 'meekness'). <em>Hotel du Lac</em> in 2020 therefore seems simultaneously terribly old-fashioned and curiously relevant.<br /><br />As in, for example, <em><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29429921.Look_At_Me" title="Look At Me by Anita Brookner" rel="nofollow noopener">Look At Me</a>,</em> the people with whom the protagonist becomes obsessed are hardly fascinating to the reader: the lives of the fussy, indulgent Mrs Pusey and her daughter Jennifer seemed to me more depressing and unenviable than Edith's. Given that a) the circle of characters at the hotel is small and b) this is an Anita Brookner novel, I knew exactly what was going to happen when Edith met a charming, if rather offhand, suitor. The revelation of the final pages came as no surprise. I liked the ending, and rather hoped she took at least some inspiration from Mr Neville's 'secret of contentment' thereafter. But you can read into it what you will, I suppose.<br /><br />I love Brookner's writing, and <em>Hotel du Lac</em> is filled with perfect sentences – I relished the one-liners (Edith saying to her agent, 'I simply do not know anyone who has a lifestyle'), the sharp description (a corridor 'vibrant with absence'). One element didn't work for me: the letters Edith writes to her former lover David. Even considering that they're unsent, the letters don't ring true, and the act of writing them doesn't fit with what we're shown of Edith's emotional landscape.<br /><br />Despite that, if I'd never read anything by Brookner before, this might have been a five-star book for me. As it was, it felt a little too familiar, and I think I am always going to feel that <em>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1634440124" rel="nofollow noopener">Look At Me</a>
</em> is her best. I'll finish with my favourite passage from <em>Hotel du Lac</em> (there's a version of this on the quotes page for the book, but it omits the last line, which is the best bit!):<br /><br /><blockquote>It is not true that Satan makes work for idle hands to do; that is just what he doesn't. Satan should be at hand with all manner of glittering distractions, false but irresistible promises, inducements to reprehensible behaviour. Instead of which one is simply offered a choice between overwork and half-hearted idleness. And that is scarcely a choice at all. One cannot even rely on Satan to fulfil his obligations.</blockquote><br /><br />Having been working from home since March, I can testify that this is indeed correct.<br /><br /><a href="https://tinyletter.com/learnthisphrase" rel="nofollow noopener">TinyLetter</a> | <a href="https://linktr.ee/learnthisphrase" rel="nofollow noopener">Linktree</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="2321154796711502486" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


