<div id="review_2780641968" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2780641968" />
    <a title="Anna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32926679-anna"><img alt="Anna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534455052p2/32926679.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2780641968?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anna" href="/user/show/32926679-anna">Anna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=all-kinds-of-love">all-kinds-of-love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=satire">satire</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=female-protagonist">female-protagonist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=pensive">pensive</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=female-author">female-author</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=read-in-english">read-in-english</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=british">british</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=booker-winner">booker-winner</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32926679-anna?shelf=writers-writing-about-other-writers">writers-writing-about-other-writers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2780641968" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1074724089615814455">This was a slow and quiet book. Substantial despite its unsubstantial size. Funny and melancholic. With a heroine that is not much of a heroine (much like Austen&apos;s Fanny Price), who seems to have resigned from her life, despite being rather attractive and quite successful as a writer. <br/><br/>Edith writes romance novels for the tortoises (as opposed to the hares), as she describes it herself, because she thinks that it is the tortoises that need them since the hares are too busy living them out. An unsp</span>
  <span id="freeText1074724089615814455" style="display:none">This was a slow and quiet book. Substantial despite its unsubstantial size. Funny and melancholic. With a heroine that is not much of a heroine (much like Austen's Fanny Price), who seems to have resigned from her life, despite being rather attractive and quite successful as a writer. <br /><br />Edith writes romance novels for the tortoises (as opposed to the hares), as she describes it herself, because she thinks that it is the tortoises that need them since the hares are too busy living them out. An unspecified faux pas brings Edith to a certain (very respectable - guests with recommendations only) Hotel du Lac in Switzerland at the end of the season when it is populated by a small but colorful cast of guests, consisting mainly of women. <br /><br />It is almost impossible to discern that the novel is taking place in the 80s because both the setting and the guests, including Edith, seem to be stuck somewhere at the beginning of the century, as if modern times and sensibilities have had no effect upon them. Brookner acknowledges this anachronism but insists on it because it makes Edith's plight both more puzzling and more dramatic. She is part of the world that is not there anymore, possessing attitudes that seem out of place in the modern world. Her romance novels are not selling very well anymore because even the tortoises are getting a hold of their own destiny. Yet one keeps thinking how much happier she could have been if she embraced modernity, accepted the freedoms that were finally becoming tangible, let go of her own prejudices and of the people who were holding her back. Can she do it or is setting herself free too much of a hassle? <br /><br />I've heard that Brookner was treated very unkindly by the literary establishment when <i>Hotel du Lac</i> won the Booker as if it was her fault that more deserving books - according to some opinions - didn't win. I find it appalling. I guess that same literary establishment would have banished Jane Austen for the smallness of her world if she were writing now. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1074724089615814455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


